# arvo-narrow. Design

The concrete narrowing layer. Hosts every `impl const Narrow<T>` for
the primitive pairs that arvo cares about. Per round 202604271346
Q-C, this lives downstream of `arvo-bitmask` (because it uses concrete
mask types). The `Narrow<T>` trait declaration lives in
`arvo-bits-contracts` (merged in from the previously-separate
`arvo-narrow-contracts` crate during round 202604280034).
`#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-storage`, `arvo-bits-contracts`,
`arvo-mask-contracts`, `arvo-bitmask`.

## Concrete impls

Per source / target pair. Pattern:

```rust
impl<S: Strategy> const Narrow<u8> for Bits<N, S>
where
    S: UContainerFor<N>,
    /* N <= 8 implied */
{
    fn narrow_to<const N: u8>(self) -> u8 {
        let mask = Mask64::mask_for_width(USize(N as usize));
        let raw_u64: u64 = self.to_raw().into();  // widened
        let masked = raw_u64 & mask.to_raw();
        masked as u8
    }
}
```

The pattern repeats with `u16`, `u32`, `u64` targets. Per-N band
selection mirrors the Hot strategy's UContainerFor projection: 1..=8
narrows to `u8`, 9..=16 to `u16`, 17..=32 to `u32`, 33..=64 to `u64`.

The exact enumeration of impl blocks (per source-strategy x target
primitive x N-band) is open during DOC iteration; the SRC CL ships
the final shape. Targeting is for clean monomorphisation across the
common consumer call sites.

## Why this lives downstream

`Narrow` impls need concrete masks. `Mask64` is in `arvo-bitmask`.
`Bits<N, S>` is in `arvo-storage`. The narrow contract surface
(`arvo-narrow-contracts`) names neither concretely; only when the impl
body is written does the dependency materialise.

Keeping `Narrow` impls in their own crate lets generic-over-narrow
consumers (the bitfield macro, the algorithm crates) bind only to
`arvo-narrow-contracts` without pulling in mask concretes. The `arvo`
facade pulls this crate to expose the common impls; consumers that
only need the trait surface get a smaller transitive footprint.

